docs.abstract: As gruesome videos and energetic protests reshape public opinion about racial discrimination, Joe Biden tried to balance protesters’ calls for a law enforcement overhaul while not alienating moderate voters.
docs.snippet: As gruesome videos and energetic protests reshape public opinion about racial discrimination, Joe Biden tried to balance protesters’ calls for a law enforcement overhaul while not alienating moderate voters.
docs.lead_paragraph: Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. staked out a careful position on Monday in support of a law enforcement overhaul but not defunding police departments, rebutting a new Republican attack line as he tries to harness growing activism against systemic racism while not alienating protesters or more moderate voters.

headline.main: Biden Walks a Cautious Line as He Opposes Defunding the Police
headline.print_headline: Biden Stopping Short of Push to Defund

docs.abstract: Our city is a coronavirus hot spot. We were only trying to protect him.
docs.snippet: Our city is a coronavirus hot spot. We were only trying to protect him.
docs.lead_paragraph: Our 16-year-old son asked us if he could attend a Black Lives Matter protest march in our city, a Covid-19 hot spot. We said no. We decided it was too dangerous in terms of coronavirus risk and possible violence. He sneaked out of the apartment and went anyway. He claims he wore a mask and was socially distant the whole time, but we’re not sure whether to believe him or how to punish him. Any advice?

headline.main: We Told Our Son Not to Protest. He Did Anyway. Now What?

docs.abstract: Before hitting like or retweet on a post about the protests, it’s important to know that the accounts you are following are trustworthy.
docs.snippet: Before hitting like or retweet on a post about the protests, it’s important to know that the accounts you are following are trustworthy.
docs.lead_paragraph: With the combination of camera phones and social media, more people than ever are being made aware of incidents of police brutality and racial inequality, and of the protests they have touched off.But making sense of the deluge of posts in the present moment can be difficult.

docs.abstract: Curators surveyed the area outside the White House on Wednesday for artifacts that will help record the emotional turmoil.
docs.snippet: Curators surveyed the area outside the White House on Wednesday for artifacts that will help record the emotional turmoil.
docs.lead_paragraph: History — painful, at times angry, history — unfolded outside the White House in the past week and curators from the Smithsonian Institution toured the area on Wednesday to begin collecting the art, signs, photographs and other artifacts that multiplied there during the recent protests over George Floyd’s death.

headline.main: Museums Collect Protest Signs to Preserve History in Real Time
headline.print_headline: For Museums, the Signs of the Times Beckon

docs.abstract: They say the mayor has benefited politically from pledges to overhaul the Police Department, but has failed to deliver meaningful change.
docs.snippet: They say the mayor has benefited politically from pledges to overhaul the Police Department, but has failed to deliver meaningful change.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mayor Bill de Blasio looked out into a sea of protesters at a memorial with George Floyd’s brother in Brooklyn last week and delivered a bold promise: He would transform the New York Police Department. “Change that you can see and believe, because you will see it with your own eyes,” he declared.

headline.main: ‘We Want to See Action’: Why Black Supporters Are Deserting de Blasio
headline.print_headline: Black Voters Lifted Up de Blasio. Now, They Boo.

docs.snippet: In a speech in Philadelphia, Mr. Biden assailed the president’s handling of the protests over police brutality and racial justice, declaring that he had “turned this country into a battlefield.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Joseph R. Biden Jr. on Tuesday excoriated President Trump’s stewardship of a nation convulsed in crisis over racism and police brutality, likening Mr. Trump’s language to that of Southern racists of the 1960s while also warning Americans that “we cannot let our rage consume us.”

headline.main: Joe Biden Laces Into Trump for Fanning ‘Flames of Hate’
